{
  "texts": [
    "This proposal offered necessary scaffolds for coordinated inquiry substantiating the DSA's role in this transition while shaping future adaptations.",
    "Appendix 1: Defining disinformation in the DSAAs defined in our footnote at page 2 in Sect. 1, throughout this research paper we referred to disinformation according to the European Democracy Action Plan's definition (EDAP) i.e., \"false or misleading content that is spread with an intention to deceive or secure economic or political gain and which may cause public harm.\"",
    "While disinformation is often used interchangeably with misinformation in the literature, the latter presents a slightly different nuance.",
    "According to the EDAP, \"misinformation is false or misleading content shared without harmful intent, though the effects can still be harmful, e.g., when people share false information with friends and family in good faith.\"",
    "The nuance between the two terms lies in the intention for dissemination, which may be challenging to determine a priori."
  ]
}